  <static seed="1285" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions130.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{y^{2}-4y+3}{2y-y^{2}-1}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{y-3}{y-1}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors.</p>
<p>If a polynomial is not in order, we order it by the variable<rsq/>s degrees.</p>
<p>If the leading coefficient is negative, we factor out <m>-1</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{y^{2}-4y+3}{2y-y^{2}-1}} \amp = \frac{{\left(y-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)}}{{-y^{2}+2y-1}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{\left(y-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)}}{{-\left(y^{2}-2y+1\right)}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{\left(y-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-1\right)}}{{-\left(y-1\right)^{2}}} \\
                     \amp = {-\frac{y-3}{y-1}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>y - 1</m> was crossed out, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>y \ne 1</m>.</p>
</solution>
